'''Equinet''' is the '''European Network of Equality Bodies'''. It serves as a professional platform for cooperation, capacity building and peer support amongst equality bodies around the legal interpretation and implementation in practice of the EU equal treatment Directives and around the promotion of equality and the elimination of discrimination.<ref name="Equinet">{{cite web|last=Equinet|title=Strategic Plan 2015-2018|url=http://www.equineteurope.org/spip.php?action=telecharger&arg=1754&type=application.pdf|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>

Equinet currently consists of 46 Equality Bodies from 34 different European countries. Members of Equinet have been established on the basis of the [[List of European Union directives#Anti-discrimination measures|EU equal treatment Directives]] and they are empowered to counteract discrimination across the range of grounds including [[Ageing|age]], [[disability]], [[gender]], [[Race (human classification)|race]] or [[ethnic origin]], [[religion]] or [[belief]], and [[sexual orientation]].<ref name="age-platform">{{cite web|last=AGE|title=Factsheet on Equinet|url=http://www.age-platform.eu/images/stories/EN/pdf_AGE_Factsheet_on_Equinet-2.pdf|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>

==History==
Equinet builds upon the two-year project "''Strengthening the co-operation between specialised bodies for the implementation of equal treatment legislation''" (2002-2004).<ref>{{cite web|last=Gunda Werner Institute|title=Institutions Of The EU Commission And Parliament|url=http://www.gwi-boell.de/web/eu-gender-politics-institutions-eu-commission-3055.html|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>   The initiative to create a network of equality bodies was taken by the Migration Policy Group,<ref>{{cite web|last=Migration Policy Group|title=Migration Policy Group|url=http://www.migpolgroup.com/|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> who also acted as Equinet's Secretariat until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|last=Migration Policy Group|title=Project: Equality bodies|url=http://www.migpolgroup.com/projects_detail.php?id=26}}</ref>  Equinet was established as an independent structure in 2007 with the creation of the Equinet Secretariat in Brussels and its registration as a not-for-profit international association ([[AISBL]]) under [[Belgian law]].<ref>{{cite web|last=European Commission|title=EU action against discrimination Activity report 2007-08|url=http://www.igfse.pt/upload/docs/gabdoc/2009/Novidades/07-Jul/EU%20action%20against%20discrimination_Activity%20report%202007-08.pdf|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>

==Mission==
Equinet is the European network of equality bodies. The network promotes equality in Europe through supporting and enabling the work of national equality bodies. It supports equality bodies to be independent and effective as valuable catalysts for more equal societies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Equinet|title=Equinet at a Glance|url=http://www.equineteurope.org/-About-us-|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>   Apart from being a platform for exchange among member equality bodies, Equinet contributes to the wider European debate on matters of equal-treatment and non-discrimination by sharing the experience of equality bodies through so-called perspectives aimed at equality experts and policy-makers.<ref>{{cite web|last=SIPU International|title=Review of EU Networks for Civil Society Organizations|url=http://zaklada.civilnodrustvo.hr/upload/File/hr/izdavastvo/digitalna_zbirka/eu_networks.pdf|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>

==Activities==
Equinet attempts to strengthen the voice and contributions of national equality bodies to the wider European equality debate. Equinet's input in advancing equality is achieved by:<ref name="Equinet Strategic Plan 2015-2018">{{cite web|last=Equinet Webpage|title=Strategic Plan 2015-2018|url=http://www.equineteurope.org/spip.php?action=telecharger&arg=1754&type=application.pdf|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>
*Building capacity and peer support of equality bodies
*Contributing to the European equality agenda
*Serving as a knowledge and communication hub on equal treatment 
*Consolidating the network and the position of its members

Equinet is an umbrella organisation for European equality bodies and has no mandate to provide any kind of legal assistance to individual victims of discrimination. The organisation however provides contact details (see next section) for equality bodies based in all EU members states and beyond.<ref>{{cite web|last=AGE|title=Factsheet on Equinet|url=http://www.age-platform.eu/images/stories/EN/pdf_AGE_Factsheet_on_Equinet-2.pdf|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>   EU anti-discrimination legislation provides that each Member State shall have (at least) one such equality body with the power to, among other, give independent assistance to victims of discrimination. The equality bodies are specialised authorities whose staff are trained and experienced to handle cases of discrimination.<ref>{{cite web|last=ENAR - European Network Against Racism|title=What you can do if you are a victim of racial/ethnic discrimination|url=http://www.enar-eu.org/Page_Generale.asp?DocID=29966&lb=3884|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>

==Members==
Most Equinet members belong to the [[European Union]], while six equality bodies come from outside the European Union ([[Albania]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Norway]] and [[Serbia]]).

